  "prompt": "When should we change dusk brakes?",
  "response": "Dusk brakes could be a typo, and you might be referring to \"brake pads.\" If that's the case, here are some signs that you may need to change your brake pads:\n\n1. **Squeaking or Screeching Noise**: Most brake pads have a built-in wear indicator that makes a high-pitched noise when the pads are worn out.\n\n2. **Grinding Noise**: If you hear a grinding sound when braking, this may indicate that the brake pads are worn down completely, which can damage the rotor.\n\n3. **Vibration or Pulsation**: If you feel a pulsation in the brake pedal when braking, it might indicate that the rotors are warped or that the brake pads are unevenly worn.\n\n4. **Warning Light**: Some vehicles have a warning light on the dashboard that indicates when the brake pads need to be replaced.\n\n5. **Reduced Responsiveness**: If you notice that it takes longer to stop than usual, your brake pads may be worn out.\n\n6. **Thinning Pads**: Visually inspect the brake pads. If they appear thin (less than 1/4 inch), it\u2019s a good idea to replace them.\n\n7. **Mileage**: Generally, brake pads should be checked at least every 20,000 to 50,000 miles, but this can vary based on driving habits and vehicle type.\n\nIt's always best to consult your vehicle's owner\u2019s manual for specific recommendations and to have a professional mechanic inspect your brakes if you're unsure. Regular brake maintenance is essential for safety.",
